name: proteasome endopeptidase complex
reaction: Cleavage of peptide bonds with very broad specificity
comment: A 20-S protein composed of 28 subunits arranged in four rings of seven. The outer rings are composed of alpha subunits, but the beta subunits forming the inner rings are responsible for peptidase activity. In eukaryotic organisms there are up to seven different types of beta subunits, three of which may carry the N-terminal threonine residues that are the nucleophiles in catalysis, and show different specificities. The molecule is barrel-shaped, and the active sites are on the inner surfaces. Terminal apertures restrict access of substrates to the active sites. There is evidence that catalytic subunits are replaced by others under some conditions so as to alter the specificity of proteolysis, perhaps optimizing it for the formation of antigenic peptides. A complex of the 20-S proteasome endopeptidase complex with a 19-S regulatory unit is the 26-S proteasome that degrades ubiquitin-protein conjugates. Type example of peptidase family T1.
